-- Stocks in South Africa Fall to Two-Week Low, Led by MTN, Billiton, Anglo
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-11-23T16:15:18Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-23/bhp-billiton-sasol-anglo-american-lead-decline-in-south-african-equities.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  plunged the most in three months, losing 508.74, or
1.6 percent, to 30,895.07 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Adcock Ingram Holdings Ltd.  (AIP SJ), South Africa’s
second-largest pharmaceutical company, dropped 49 cents, or 0.7
percent, to 66.50 rand, a second day of decreases. Profit for
the year through September fell to 631.5 million rand ($90
million) from 782.4 million rand a year earlier.  Anglo Platinum Ltd. (AMS SJ), the world’s biggest producer
of the metal, fell for the second consecutive day, declining 14
rand, or 2 percent, to 676 rand. Platinum dropped as much as 1.6
percent, to $1,636 an ounce.  Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd.  (IMP
SJ), the second-largest producer, retreated for a third day,
losing 2.06 rand, or 1 percent, to 209.50 rand.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up 10 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, slipped 5.5 rand, or 1.7 percent, to 319 rand, the lowest
since Oct. 27. Copper dropped as much as 2.9 percent to $8,050 a
metric ton on the London Metal Exchange. Stocks and commodities
retreated after North and South Korea exchanged artillery fire
and on speculation an Irish bailout will fail to stem Europe’s
debt crisis. Lead, tin and zinc all slumped.  African Rainbow
Minerals Ltd.  (ARI SJ), a South African mining company, slipped
6.63 rand, or 3.4 percent, to 189.50 rand.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, dropped for the second day in three, weakening 3.96
rand, or 1.5 percent, to 255.49 rand. BHP Billiton said rain has
affected coal-mining operations and high winds and seas have
disrupted loading at its terminal at Hay Point port in
Australia’s Queensland state.  Kelly Group Ltd.  (KEL SJ), a staffing company, declined 20
cents, or 4.4 percent, to 4.30 rand, the first drop in seven
days. The group said its earnings before one-time items in the
year through September plunged 54 percent to 26.3 million rand.  MTN Group Ltd.  (MTN SJ), Africa’s largest mobile phone
company, snapped two days of gains, plunged the most since March
25, dropping 6.05 rand, or 4.6 percent, to 124.50 rand, the
lowest since Oct. 28. The rand, in which MTN reports its
earnings, depreciated to the lowest in a week against the
dollar, the currency in which MTN’s international revenue is
accounted.  Old Mutual Plc  (OML SJ), the third-biggest insurer in the
U.K., weakened for the seventh consecutive day, losing 26 cents,
or 1.8 percent, to 13.90 rand. Stocks and commodities retreated
after North and South Korea exchanged artillery fire and on
speculation an Irish bailout will fail to stem Europe’s debt
crisis.  Pick n Pay Stores Ltd.  (PIK SJ), South Africa’s second-
largest grocer, had a third day of declines, retreating 54
cents, or 1.1 percent, to 47.98 rand, the lowest since Nov. 3.
The company had its recommendation downgraded to “sell” from
“hold,” by Investec Ltd. equity analyst  Kirsty Laschinger , who
placed a 12-month price estimate of 45.57 rand a share. Pick n
Pay also said in a regulatory filing it has agreed with
Australia’s Metcash Trading Ltd. to extend the deadline for the
sale of its Franklins to Metcash until June 2011.  Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, declined for a second day, losing 10.40 rand, or
3.1 percent, to 322.60 rand. Oil fell as much as 1.8 percent to
$80.28 a barrel.  To contact the reporter on this story:
